value.0: Caldrian shivers in the mine's damp. "Help yourself to some rat, <FirstName>. It looks like we'll be here a while."
Against the far wall, a piece of chalk suddenly scrapes against the rock. You turn to see a new message forming in the young elf's familiar scrawl but it is not his hand that holds the chalk.
You find it hard to swallow past the lump that's forming in your throat. Something tells you that you knew this ghostly woman once.

Slowly the spirit lets the piece of chalk fall to the cavern floor and turns to you. Filled with dread, you read the words she just inscribed: <StartAction>"The fields of battle lie in the hearts of men..."</Start>

Meat sizzles on a nearby spit, the aroma mingling with the harsher scents of rust and rock-dust. The fire casts dancing shadows on the cavern walls and, in the flickering light, you see the dim outline of a man.

He leans against an anvil, his shoulders hunched, his head buried deep within his hands. As you draw closer, you can see the soiled remnants of a familiar uniform hanging in rags from his waif-like form.
The man raises his head from his hands and begins to speak. "I know you, don't I?" he asks, his voice hopeful. He moves his face into the light. "You recognize me, right?"
The man raises his head from his hands and begins to speak. "I know you, don't I?" he asks, squinting to see you better in the light. "The armor," his sad eyes confess, "that's all I recognize."

"Fine, but be careful. The rats are getting in from somewhere. I've lost count of how many I've killed but there's always more... I'll stay here and mind the fire. Bring back some meat if you want it cooked."
The young man straightens, suddenly alert. "What do you mean you don't remember? It's happening to all of us, isn't it! We're all forgetting. Everything... it's just gone."
The young man hunches even further into the gloom. "Well someone must think otherwise or they wouldn't have thrown you in here... But what do I know? I've forgotten everything."
The young man stares off into the distance. "Caldrian Ayre. I remember that much, at least." His bloodshot eyes seem haunted within his grime-darkened features. "Everything else I've forgotten."
"The king?" You watch him struggle to put meaning to the word. "I guess so," he concedes. "I've forgotten everything."
The young man glances over to the crude spit nearby, blushing a little beneath the dirt. "Rat," he admits. "The meat's a little tough but at least there's an ample supply."

The elf shrugs, all skin and bones. He doesn't seem to know who you're referring to. "I'm sorry, I don't know what to say. Something must have gone wrong. All I've got is what I managed to write down."
He runs his fingers through his hair, leaving it tousled and peaked. His almond eyes close in frustration and he turns his face upward to some imagined sky. "We've been worked," he sighs.
"We've been witchworked. Magicked... How else would you explain it?" The elf pounds his fist into the anvil's cold steel. "Maybe there's something in what I've written down."
"I've been trying to write things down so I'll remember but, when I read them back, half of them don't even seem to make sense."
"I don't know, I keep on coming across new messages." Grease sputters in the fire but the young man doesn't look away. "Here's what I've been able to piece together."
"I'm apparently loyal to some prince," he says, his face earnest. "That must have been important because I had put it in big letters."

The young man listens carefully. "I'm loyal to Prince Ahmed," he whispers as he scratches the words onto the floor, "but he is dead." He pockets the chalk solemnly, wiping the dust on his grubby tunic.
"I think I'm from someplace called Barak'Thule. We all are, I think. I drew a rough map but all it really shows is that Barak'Thule is somewhere far southwest of here."
"When I was hunting rats, I found a message about that. It was underlined..." Shadows dance across his face.
"We're a company of Witch Hunters, <Sir/Madam>, in the king's service. We had tracked one here to some cliffs beyond the pass."
Sensing your rising dread, your newfound friend opens his mouth to speak. A sudden gust of wind fuels the fire, however. With the change of light, your blood runs cold.
Sensing your excitement, your newfound friend opens his mouth to speak. A sudden gust of wind fuels the fire, however. With the change of light, your blood runs cold.
Against the far wall, a piece of chalk suddenly scrapes against the rock. You turn to see a new message forming in the young elf's familiar scrawl but it is not his hand that holds the chalk.
You find it hard to swallow past the lump that's forming in your throat. Something tells you that you knew this ghostly woman once.

Slowly the spirit lets the piece of chalk fall to the cavern floor and turns to you. Filled with dread, you read the words she just inscribed: <StartAction>"The fields of battle lie in the hearts of men..."</Start>
A guilty look flashes across the young elf's almond eyes. "Only that it's safe. I hid it somewhere before they caught me but the note I left didn't mention where."
He looks crestfallen as he makes his confession. "Yes, <Sir/Madam>, I wrote that down, too. I don't know what would have made me do that. Maybe the prince commanded it."
He digs for his chalk. "What's the message?"
The elf scrawls the message onto the anvil. "Who is it referring to?" he asks.
He straightens. "Don't worry, <Sir/Madam>. We'll get your message delivered." His youthful confidence takes you by surprise and, for the first time days, you allow yourself to smile.
He straightens. "Don't worry, <Sir/Madam>. We'll figure it out." His youthful confidence takes you by surprise and, for the first time in what feels like days, you allow yourself to smile.
He takes the scrawled message from your hand and reads it in his mother tongue. "'Bryn que Cardis Cavanyl d'ru velm a Llorys Brogue, za'et a llandar que moygre eyr qaddara que maar...'"
"'If the Cavanaugh Stone gave birth to Brogan's Tears, then to find the mother I must pursue the child.' ...Maybe I wrote it," he finally sighs. "If you know me so well, why don't you tell me?"
Leave.
"Goodbye."
"Yuh, maybe. Me not remember."
"Maybe. I don't remember."
"Me doubt it."
"I doubt it."
"You have name?"
"What's your name?"
"Yuh, we both work for the king."
"Yes, we both worked in service to the king."
"Mmm, what you cooking?"
"What are you cooking?"
"Night Hag say you have answers."
"The Night Hag told me you'd have answers."
"How someone forget *everything*?"
"How does one forget *everything*?"
"Worked? What you mean?"
"Worked? What do you mean?"
"Yuh, me forget everything too."
"I've forgotten everything too."
"What you write down?"
"What have you written down?"
"What else you write down?"
"What else did you write down?"
"That be Prince Ahmed. He be all dead."
"His name's Prince Ahmed. He's dead."
"Who we be then? Why we come so far?"
"Who are we? Why are we so far from home?"
"This be for sure?"
"You're sure of this?"
"The Night Hag? She be witch?"
"The Night Hag? Is she the witch?"
"She be dead... 'Tell the king the witch be dead!'"
"She is dead... 'Tell the king the witch is dead!'"
"You find anything about Cavanaugh Stone?"
"Did you find anything about the Cavanaugh Stone?"
"Me have message for king of Barak'Thule."
"I have a message for the king of Bark'Thule."
"You remember that you steal it, yuh?"
"You remember that you stole it, don't you?"
"Me have message to bring to that place's king."
"I have a message to bring to the king there."
"Sorry. It be a secret."
"Sorry, it's confidential."
"Prince say to tell king that she be dead."
"Prince Ahmed said to tell the king that she is dead."
"Sorry, it be a secret."
"Sorry, it's confidential."
"Me wish me knew."
"I wish I knew."
"Did you write this message in the Guild Exhibits?"
"I don't remember anything, all right?"
"But I don't know you."
"Calm down. We both work in service to the king."
